{{Infobox person | name = Indriati Iskak | image = Indriati Iskak in a promotional still (c. 1960), by Tati Photo Studio.jpg{{!}}300px | alt = | caption = Indriati Iskak in c. 1960 | birth_name = <!--only use if different from name--> | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1942|06|09}} <!-- {{Birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Birth-date and age|df=yes|Month DD, YYYY}} --> | birth_place = [[Surabaya]], [[East Java]] | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = [[Indonesia]]n | other_names = | occupation = Actress, marketer }} {{Indonesian name|patronymic=yes|Iskak|Indriati}} '''Indriati Gerald Bernardina''' (born 9 June 1942), also known by her stage name '''Indriati Iskak''' and after marriage as '''Indri Makki''', is an Indonesian actress turned psychologist and marketer. Born in [[Surabaya]], she entered the Indonesian film industry and soared to popularity with [[Usmar Ismail]]'s commercially successful ''[[Tiga Dara]]'' (1957). She appeared in eight further films and established her own [[girl group]] before retiring from cinema in 1963. She graduated from the [[University of Indonesia]] with a degree in psychology in 1968, and has taught the subject at the {{Interlanguage link multi|Jakarta Art Institute|id|3=Institut Kesenian Jakarta}}. For twenty-six years she worked with [[Unilever]], and since 1994 she has been a marketing consultant with Makki Makki.
==Biography== Indriati Iskak was born in [[Surabaya]], [[East Java]], on 9 June 1942. She is the daughter of Raden Iskak,{{sfn|Biran|1979|p=228}} an educator who transitioned to film in 1952, when he became the director of ''[[Penjelendup]]'' (''Smuggler'').{{sfn|Biran|1979|p=406}}
Indriati made her feature film debut in [[Usmar Ismail]]'s ''[[Tiga Dara]]'' (''Three Maidens'') in 1957, starring alongside [[Chitra Dewi]] and [[Mieke Wijaya]]. She portrayed Nenny, the youngest of three sisters raised by their grandmother after their mother's death.{{sfn|Kristanto|2007|p=46}} The film was a massive popular success, and Indriati, who was praised for having a more naturalistic acting style than her stage-trained fellow actors, saw the greatest popularity of her co-stars.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=152}}
The following year Indriati appeared in another of Ismail's film, ''[[Sengketa]]'' (''Conflict'', 1957). She again played the daughter in a family fraught with difficulties.{{sfn|Kristanto|2007|pp=48&ndash;49}} After this film, Indriati completed two productions with Djuprihadi's Stupa Film, both under the direction of [[Wim Umboh]]: ''[[Djuara Sepatu Roda]]'' (''Roller Skating Champion'', 1958) and ''[[Tiga Mawar]]'' (''Three Roses'', 1959).{{sfn|Kristanto|2007|pp=50, 52}} With [[Rima Melati]], {{Interlanguage link multi|Gaby Mambo|id}}, and [[Baby Huwae]], she formed a [[girl group]] named the Baby Dolls in 1959.{{sfn|Biran|1979|p=228}}
Indriati continued acting through 1963,{{sfn|Biran|1979|p=228}} when she made her last film, ''[[Daun Emas]]'' (''Golden Leaves''). It was directed by her father and co-starred her brother Boy<!--Yes, that's his name-->.{{sfn|Kristanto|2007|p=64}} Indriati's popularity during the 1950s and 1960s has been credited with leading Indonesian film directors to seek out [[Indo people|Indo]]-looking actresses for their films, and thus precipitating the careers of film stars such as [[Lydia Kandou]], [[Meriam Bellina]], and [[Tamara Bleszynski]].{{sfn|Apa Siapa|1999|p=238}} Advertising for [[Perfini]]'s ''[[Asrama Dara]]'' (''Dormitory for Girls''; 1958) touted its young star [[Suzzanna]], an Indo girl from [[Bogor]], as the next Indriati Iskak.{{sfn|Imanjaya|2006|p=112}}
After ''Daun Emas'', Indriati retired from acting and went to university, completing a degree in psychology at the [[University of Indonesia]] in 1968.{{sfn|Biran|1979|p=228}} After some time working at the Indonesian Air Force's psychological counselling bureau, in the 1970s she began working at [[Unilever]].{{sfn|Biran|1979|p=228}} She stayed with the company for twenty-six years, at first handling market research before moving on to marketing management and advertising. Towards the end of her time with Unilever, she oversaw the computerisation of the company's Indonesia branch.{{sfn|Makki Makki, Indri}} In the mid-1970s Indriati also taught psychology at the {{Interlanguage link multi|Jakarta Art Institute|id|3=Institut Kesenian Jakarta}},{{sfn|Biran|1979|p=228}} and for fifteen years she was on the board of the Strada system of [[Catholicism in Indonesia|Catholic]] schools.{{sfn|Makki Makki, Indri}}
Indriati married an [[Indonesian Air Force]] officer,{{sfn|Anwar|1991|p=3}} Makki Perdanakusuma (the younger brother of [[Halim Perdanakusuma]]), in 1962. The couple had three children: Sania Makki, Sakti Makki, and Sari Makki. They remained married until Makki Perdanakusuma's death in 2014.{{sfn|Prabowo|2014}} {{As of|2016}}, Indriati is a branding consultant with Makki Makki, having worked there since 1994. Her daughter Sania and son Sakti also work for the company.{{sfn|Makki Makki, Indri}}
==Filmography== During her six-year film career, Indriati appeared in nine films.{{sfn|Biran|1979|p=228}}{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Filmography}} {{Div col|colwidth=25em}} *''[[Tiga Dara]]'' (1956) *''[[Sengketa]]'' (1957) *''[[Djuara Sepatu Roda]]'' (1958) *''[[Tiga Mawar]]'' (1959) *''[[Desa yang Dilupakan]]'' (1960) *''[[Gadis Diseberang Djalan]]'' (1960) *''[[Djantung Hati]]'' (1961) *''[[Masih Ada Hari Esok]]'' (1961) *''[[Daun Emas]]'' (1963) {{div col end}}
